sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K2066109
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Parts are from registry with the exception of UNS backbone (WM16_iGEM universal primer) which comes from Torella et. al 2013 ("Rapid construction of insulated genetic circuits via synthetic sequence-guided isothermal assembly")
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part places both pTet GFP and it's repressor TetR on the same plasmid, which both reduces metabolic stress on transformed cells and helps limit the number of plasmids used by the circuit control toolbox. Placing all circuit control parts on a single plasmid will allow a workable number of plasmids to be used for the input circut to the circuit control toolbox circuit.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This part contains a spacer which can be used to amplify either of the inserts to check for errors. This spacer sequence is derived from UNS6 from Torella et. al 2013
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kalen Clifton, Christine Gao, Andrew Halleran, Ethan Jones, Likhitha Kolla, Joseph Maniaci, John Marken, John Mitchell, Callan Monette, Adam Reiss

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K2066018
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: UNS 2 Sequence, from Torella et al., 2013
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Torella, J. P., Boehm, C. R., Lienert, F., Chen, J. H., Way, J. C., & Silver, P. A. (2013). Rapid construction of insulated genetic circuits via synthetic sequence-guided isothermal assembly. Nucleic acids research, gkt860.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is Unique Nucleotide Sequence 2, (UNS 2), from Torella et al., 2013. The William and Mary iGEM team has adopted this as our standard prefix; as such, all of our parts will have this sequence immediately following the BioBrick prefix. We took this measure in order to allow easier Gibson Assembly cloning of our parts. Primer sequences which can be used to clone with the UNS 2/3 standard can be found on our wiki.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: UNS 2 was chosen because it works well with UNS 3 and it is in accordance with the BioBrick standard.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kalen Clifton, Christine Gao, Andrew Halleran, Ethan Jones, Likhitha Kolla, Joseph Maniaci, John Marken, John Mitchell, Callan Monette, Adam Reiss

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: p(tetR)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Lutz, R., Bujard, H., Nucleic Acids Research (1997) 25, 1203-1210.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Sequence for pTet inverting regulator driven by the TetR protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: BBa_R0040 TetR-Regulated Promoter is based on a cI promoter. It has been modified to include two TetR binding sites and the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K2066019
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: UNS 3 Sequence, from Torella et al., 2013
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Torella, J. P., Boehm, C. R., Lienert, F., Chen, J. H., Way, J. C., & Silver, P. A. (2013). Rapid construction of insulated genetic circuits via synthetic sequence-guided isothermal assembly. Nucleic acids research, gkt860.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This is Unique Nucleotide Sequence 3, (UNS 3), from Torella et al., 2013. The William and Mary iGEM team has adopted this as our standard prefix; as such, all of our parts will have this sequence immediately following the BioBrick prefix. We took this measure in order to allow easier Gibson Assembly cloning of our parts. Primer sequences which can be used to clone with the UNS 2/3 standard can be found on our wiki.
The sequence for this part came from the following paper: Torella, J. P., Boehm, C. R., Lienert, F., Chen, J. H., Way, J. C., & Silver, P. A. (2013). Rapid construction of insulated genetic circuits via synthetic sequence-guided isothermal assembly. Nucleic acids research, gkt860. A huge thanks to all the researchers involved in its original creation!
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This UNS sequence was chosen to serve as the 3' primer in our standard because it works well with UNS 2 and it adheres to the BioBrick standards.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kalen Clifton, Christine Gao, Andrew Halleran, Ethan Jones, Likhitha Kolla, Joseph Maniaci, John Marken, John Mitchell, Callan Monette, Adam Reiss

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0015
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Double terminator consisting of BBa_B0010 and BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: tetR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the TetR protein without the Ribosome Binding Site. Modified with an LVA tail for rapid degradation of the protein and faster fall time for the emission. TetR binds to the pTet regulator (BBa_R0040). aTc (anhydrotetracycline) binds to TetR and inhibits its operation.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999).

Lutz R, Bujard H., Independent and tight regulation of transcriptional units in Escherichia coli via the LacR/O, the TetR/O and AraC/I1-I2 regulatory elements. Nucleic Acids Res. 1997 Mar 15;25(6):1203-10. PMID: 9092630

References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999).

Lutz R, Bujard H., Independent and tight regulation of transcriptional units in Escherichia coli via the LacR/O, the TetR/O and AraC/I1-I2 regulatory elements. Nucleic Acids Res. 1997 Mar 15;25(6):1203-10. PMID: 9092630

BBa_C0040 TetR Protein is based on the TetR sequence from Elowitz's repressilator. It has been modified to include a rapid degradation LVA tail, and includes the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites. The RBS has been removed. The stop codon has been changed from TAA to a double stop codon TAATAA.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0031
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Medium RBS based on Ron Weiss thesis. Strength considered relative to <bb_part>BBa_B0030</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0032</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0033</bb_part>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix ("RBS-1" in figure 4-14 of thesis).

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS.

Contact info for this part: Brian Cho
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K2066507
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: UNS 6.1 sequence derived from (Torella et. al 2013) "Rapid construction of insulated genetic circuits via synthetic sequence-guided isothermal assembly".
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is used as a spacer. WM iGEM 2016 used this part as a spacer to connect two separate composite parts onto the same plasmid. For example, UNS 6.1 was used as a spacer to connect K2066022(TetR on UNS) and K2066023(pTET GFP on UNS) to make K2066053.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Used this part as a spacer.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kalen Clifton, Christine Gao, Andrew Halleran, Ethan Jones, Likhitha Kolla, Joseph Maniaci, John Marken, John Mitchell, Callan Monette, Adam Reiss

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K2066530
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: TACTAG spacer, exists so that we can manually insert correct scar sequences
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Joseph L Maniaci

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg
